      <div xml:id="NA38-kiḷavi">
        <p type="edition">itu talaivi vaṉpuṟai (G1+2: vaṉpoṟai) etiraḻintu colliyatu.</p>
        <p type="translation" xml:lang="en">This is what SHE said in answer to consolation.</p>
      </div>
      <div xml:id="NA38">
        <lg type="edition">
<l>            vēṭṭam poyyātu valaivaḷañ ciṟappap</l>
<l>            pāṭṭam poyyātu paratavar pakara</l>
<l>            virumpaṉan tīmpiḻi yuṇpōr makiḻu</l>
<l>            mārkali yāṇart tāyiṉun tōṭukeḻu</l>
<l>            mellam pulampaṉ piriyiṟ pulleṉap </l>
<l>            pulampā kiṉṟē tōḻi kalaṅkunīrk</l>
<l>            kaḻicūḻ paṭappaik kāṇṭa vāyi</l>
<l>            lolikā vōlai muṇmiṭai vēlip</l>
<l>            peṇṇai yivaru māṅkaṇ</l>
<l>            veṇmaṇaṟ paṭappaiyem maḻuṅka lūrē.</l>
            </lg>
        <lg type="translation" xml:lang="en">

<l>Even if the loudly roaring [sea?]<note place="foot"><term xml:lang="ta">ārkali</term> is, according to T.V.G., to be understood as a <term xml:lang="sa">bahuvrīhi</term> denoting "sea".</note> is fertile,</l>
<l rend="indent2">where the eaters are delighted,</l>
<l rend="indent3">pressing out the sweet of the dark palmyra leaf,</l>
<l rend="indent">while the fishermen, unfailing [as?] a shower, announce [the price],</l>
<l rend="indent2">since the income of [their] nets, unfailing in hunt, is excellent,</l>
<l>when the wealthy(?)<note place="foot"><term xml:lang="ta">ōṭukeḻu</term>: this better attested variant is not doubt the lectio difficilior (it might refer to HIS possessions); <term xml:lang="ta">tērkeḻu</term>, "having a chariot", is much easier to understand and more to the point of the message.</note>, tender man from the lonely [shore] separated,</l>
<l rend="indent4">empty,</l>
<l rend="indent2">it has become lonely, friend,</l>
<l rend="indent2">− our noisy village with gardens in the white sands,</l>
<l rend="indent">in that place, where palmyra trees climb into</l>
<l rend="indent">hedges dense with thorns [and] palm-leaves in rustling groves,</l>
<l rend="indent">in Kāṇṭavāyil, gardens surrounded by backwaters</l>
<l rend="indent4">with stirring water.</l>
        </lg>
